What does it mean to create a legacy project.  What is your vision of a “dream home”. My goal is to take what a client has envisioned, marry that vision to a site, and utilize the best materials and methods to create a product that fits them “hand-in-glove”. A legacy home speaks to multiple generations and brings an investment grade quality to the endeavor. … and I love it when a client experiences a dream come to life.
@nascar today, @atlhawks last night.  Having a blast with Brett.  #101thingsiloveaboutmykids

Creating a legacy means, among other things, that materials should patina well.  In other words, the design should become more beautiful as it ages.  Imagine moss growing on the north side of a stone wall or the slight bleed of green from weathered copper.  Natural materials always represent “legacy” better.

A new project on 30A.  Florida’s gulf coast never disappoints.  Waterfront properties, bay front, walkability, and new urbanism define this oasis.  Creating legacy residential and commercial architecture for the region defines our passion @christopherai

There are some subjective and objective components of design.  In order to fall into the “objective” camp there has to longevity and sustainability.  In other words, people from multiple generations are drawn to it.  Creating something objectively beautiful mandates we take cues from the past.  That’s why classical architecture inspires me.  But… I do like to add some modern “subjective” elements too.

Some sketch studies of a condo and residential development. 

Sketching and hand drawings have become less and less utilized in our profession. 

I have a disdain for “cut and paste” architecture (what I call taking pictures and patching into a “design”). 

Drawing (not computer generated) is a more pure way of expression and creativity. 

Computers have a place… but as AI takes over (see The Terminator for reference - ha) and computers rule our lives, I’ll keep my pencil and sketchbook handy and hope to revive some authenticity and purity in our little segment of the profession.

In the new year I’m going to talk more about the process and execution of design. 

In these images we have braces on a roof overhang, expressed fenestration elements and an arched ceiling detail… all in process. 

The lack of detailing (or the prioritization of) in design is disturbing.  When designing, a focus on the subtle and pronounced details should not be arbitrary.  In these images, you see detailed braces and window element express the exact performance they are meant to accomplish.  Don’t complicate (or fake) it.  Let design be authentic.  Natural materials, form following function…

Much of the detailing in our designs are developed from decades (cumulative) of study.  We constantly say in our office, “Be a student of design”. 

Objective beauty is proven over time.  Travel to the south of France (for example) and see how a village attracts visitors from all over the world.  The architecture is objectively beautiful.  What makes these designs incredible?  The material usage, the thoughtful detailing, and the proportions/scale. 

Drawing from the greats like Sir Edwin Lutyens and others while introducing contrasting “modern” elements allows us to create accentuation through the careful juxtaposition and contrast of complimenting themes.

When designing this estate, the scale and shape of the lot played a significant role.  Our client wanted an “entry experience”. I envisioned a sequential arrangement which incorporated diverse materials and vistas.  A courtyard with a manicured lawn would become an exterior foyer.  The cedar braces and stone water-table became a covered entry with hand-made gas lamps hanging from the splayed roof.  Limestone and reclaimed brick with a cypress roof are the staple elements in this well curated materials pallet.  All selected with the realization that they would age well and patina over time to enhance the architecture. 

Sketching to build is one of the most gratifying parts of my vocation.
